We recommended the following:
a. The MDC realigns the residual balances of completed projects to other viable developmental projects, subject to the approval of the Sangguniang Bayan;

b. The MDC conducts intensive review of the unimplemented continuing projects under the 20% DF to determine if the PPAs are still part of the vital needs of the Municipality otherwise reprogram the identified PPAs into priority PPAs;

c. The MDC indicate specific PPAs and the Municipal Budget Officer allocate budget accordingly for each area of developmental project based on the Program of Works, particularly for the Barangay Roads Development Programs and Counterpart for National and Provincial Projects; and

d. The BAC, Municipal Engineer, MPDC, and MDC properly plan and schedule all procurement activities pertaining to development projects to pave the way for their timely implementation and completion.

We recommended that management require the:

6.16.1	Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to immediately submit the liquidation report and return the savings from completed projects to the source agencies including the BGCM balances; 

6.16.2	Municipal Accountant to verify and resolve the unreconciled beginning and negative balances and prepare JEV to record adjusting entries in the books;

6.16.3	Strengthen accounting controls by performing a regular review on the journal entry and posting in the ledgers made by the accounting staff; and

6.16.4	Municipal Engineer to fast track the implementation of on-going projects.

Exhaust all possible remedies to demand liquidation of cash advances, specifically from employees of other agencies who are no longer assigned in the Municipality by sending demand letters to their Mother Agencies;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to withhold from the salary and other benefits of employees who are still connected with the Municipality the balances of their unliquidated cash advances; and

Verify the status of accounts and take appropriate legal actions for the cash shortage of the previous Municipal Treasurer amounting to P600,498.24.

2.30 We recommended that Management:
Constitute the Inventory Committee with adequate members with a representative from the GSO and MAO who will prepare a Physical Inventory Plan containing the specific assignments/duties of the committee members from start up to the targeted completion of the physical inventory;
Instruct the Inventory Committee to prioritize the completion of physical count of PPEs and prepare the RPCPPE;
Require the MAO and the GSO to come up with the reconciled balances of PPE accounts to be considered as the correct balance of the agency’s PPEs to comply with Item 5.12 of COA Circular 2020-006;
Instruct the MAO to prepare the necessary adjusting entries, if any, among others, pursuant to COA Circular No. 2020-006;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to recognize depreciation expense to all depreciable PPE accounts to ensure fairness of preparation in the financial statements and exert effort to create manual computation on the depreciation of the PPE as a guide for the correct figures and adjust accordingly any errors noted;
The Municipal Accountant effect the prompt transfer of the cost of completed projects from the Trust Fund to the General Fund books. Corresponding depreciation expenses be provided in the books in accordance with PPSAS No. 17.; and
Direct the MAO to make the necessary adjustments to correct and/or restate the balances of affected accounts and ensure proper classification of assets in the book. Onwards, use the Inventory Custodian Slip (ICS) for issuance of semi-expandable items to establish monitoring, control, and accountability over them.

We reiterated our prior year’s audit recommendation that the Management:

1. Instruct all offices to maintain a separate list or inventory of PPE under their custodianship, update property records, conduct pre-count of these PPE, and submit Departmental RPCPPE to the GSO/Inventory Committee for validation during the annual physical inventory;

2. Designate a full time General Service Officer (GSO) composed of adequate number of members or staff to prioritize the completion of the physical inventory of all the LGU’s assets, and prepare the RPCPPE for each type of PPE and reconcile with accounting records to come up with the reconciled balances of PPE accounts to be considered as the correct balance of the agency's PPEs;

3. Require the GSO/Inventory Committee and Municipal Accountant to be guided by COA Circular No. 2020-006 in the conduct of physical count of PPE, preparation of necessary documents, reconciliation procedures, and recording in the books for the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts; and 

4. The Municipal Accountant effect the prompt transfer of the cost of completed projects from the Trust Fund to the General Fund books and provide the corresponding depreciation expenses shall then be provided in the books in accordance with PPSAS No. 17.

Exhaust all possible remedies to demand liquidation of cash advances, specifically from employees of other agencies who are no longer assigned in the Municipality by sending demand letters to their Mother Agencies;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to withhold from the salary and other benefits of employees who are still connected with the Municipality the balances of their unliquidated cash advances; and

Verify the status of accounts and take appropriate legal actions for the cash shortage of the previous Municipal Treasurer amounting to P600,498.24.

We recommended to Management the following:
Instruct all offices to maintain a separate list or inventory of PPE under their custodianship, update property records, conduct pre-count of these PPE, and submit Departmental RPCPPE to the GSO/Inventory Committee for validation during the annual physical inventory;
Create a General Service Office (GSO) composed of adequate number of members or staff to prioritize the completion of the physical inventory of all the LGU’s assets, and prepare the RPCPPE for each type of PPE and reconcile with accounting records to come up with the reconciled balances of PPE accounts to be considered as the correct balance of the agency's PPEs;
Require the GSO/Inventory Committee and Municipal Accountant to be guided by COA Circular No. 2020-006 in the conduct of physical count of PPE, preparation of necessary documents, reconciliation procedures, and recording in the books for the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts; and
The Municipal Accountant effect the prompt transfer of the cost of completed projects from the Trust Fund to the General Fund books. Corresponding depreciation expenses shall then be provided in the books in accordance with PPSAS No. 17.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
Review the composition of the Accounts Payable to determine the valid claims, ensure that all recorded payables are duly supported with the required documents and drop from the books those accounts that were not supported with necessary documents;
Set-up and/or record only accounts payable with valid and complete supporting documents in adherence to Section 4(6) of PD No. 1445;
Revert prior years’ balances of accounts payable which have remained in the books for two years or more to be without valid claims in line with the provision of Section 98 of PD 1445; and
Conduct continuous and thorough evaluation on the validity of recorded payables, particularly those pertaining to prior years in order to determine the immediate appropriate action and/or necessary adjustments therewith.

We recommended that management require the:
Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to immediately submit the liquidation report and return the savings from completed projects to the source agencies including the BGCM balances;
Municipal Accountant to verify and resolve the unreconciled beginning and negative balances and prepare JEV to record adjusting entries in the books;
Strengthen accounting controls by performing a regular review on the journal entry and posting in the ledgers made by the accounting staff; and
Municipal Engineer to fast track the implementation of on-going projects.

We recommended that the City Mayor instruct the City Accountant to:
a. submit immediately the required documents;
b. stop the practice of processing payments without complete supporting documents in compliance with Section 4 (6) of PD No. 1445;
c. record purchases of goods and materials as inventory and to recognize expense upon issuance based on Report of Supplies and Materials Issued (RSMI); and
d. require issuance of goods to be supported with Request and Issue Slip (RIS).

Exhaust all possible remedies to demand liquidation of cash advances, specifically from employees of other agencies who are no longer assigned in the Municipality by sending demand letters to their Mother Agencies;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to withhold from the salary and other benefits of employees who are still connected with the Municipality the balances of their unliquidated cash advances; and

Verify the status of accounts and take appropriate legal actions for the cash shortage of the previous Municipal Treasurer amounting to P600,498.24.

Direct the Municipal Budget Officer to charge the load allowance of the LDRRMO to the regular MOOE of the agency;

Direct the LDRRMO to re-evaluate the LDRRM unimplemented activities particularly on seminars and trainings, and ensure its implementation for the succeeding year; and

Procure and maintain availability of all basic equipment for disaster preparedness especially on the items identified.

We recommended that Management install and maintain a system of internal control for the procurement, recording and monitoring of Supplies and Property, Plant and Equipment to ensure accountability, as follows:
The procurement of supplies and PPE should be strictly in accord with the APP.;
Replacement of damaged parts of vehicles/equipment be supported with Waste Material Reports (WMR).; 
The procured items be received, accepted and recorded in the Stock or Property Cards by the Supplies/Property Officer. Stock Cards and Property Cards be maintained for each type of Supplies or PPE, respectively.;
The Supply/Property Officer issues supplies/PPE to the requesting office or end-users. The issuances should be supported with Requisition and Issue Slips. The issuance of small items not to be considered as PPE be covered with Inventory Custodian Slips (ICS) and issued PPE be supported with Acknowledgment Receipt for Equipment (ARE).; 
The Accounting Office should also maintain Supplies Ledger Cards and PPE Ledger Cards for supplies and PPE, respectively.; and
The Supply/Property Office and Accounting Office reconcile their respective records regularly.

We recommended that the Accountable Officer:
Record correctly her collections and deposits in the cashbook to reflect the correct balances of her accountability at any given time.;
Reconcile the cashbook balances for collections with the cash on hand.; 
Reconcile the cashbook balances for collections with the subsidiary ledger maintained at the Municipal Accounting Office.; and
Deposit all collections regularly and intact to avoid the accumulation of cash in her hands which may be exposed to possible risk of loss and misappropriation as well as to avoid excess deposits or overage.

It is recommended the followings:

1.	Management include sufficient appropriation in the Annual Budget for SC and PWD, and for Implementation of the programs of the LCPC;
2.	Prepare plans, programs and activities for the Local Council for the Protection of Children (LCPC).

